# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: swe-practice
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] In computing, a **legacy system** is an old method, technology, computer system, or application program, "of, relating to, or being a previous or outdated computer system", yet still in use.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Often referencing a system as "legacy" means that it paved the way for the standards that would follow it.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] This can also imply that the system is out of date or in need of replacement.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] While the term usually refers to source code, it can also apply to executable code that no longer runs on a later version of a system, or requires a compatibility layer to do so.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] An example would be a classic Macintosh application which will not run natively on macOS, but runs inside the Classic environment, or a Win16 application running on Windows XP using the Windows on Windows feature in XP.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] An example of **legacy hardware** are legacy ports like PS/2 and VGA ports, and CPUs with older, incompatible instruction sets (with e.g. newer operating systems).
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Examples in **legacy software** include **legacy file formats** like .swf for Adobe Flash or .123 for Lotus 1-2-3, and text files encoded with legacy character encodings like EBCDIC.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The first use of the term *legacy* to describe computer systems probably occurred in the 1960s.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] By the 1980s it was commonly used to refer to existing computer systems to distinguish them from the design and implementation of new systems.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Legacy was often heard during a conversion process, for example, when moving data from the legacy system to a new database.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] While this term may indicate that some engineers may feel that a system is out of date, a legacy system can continue to be used for a variety of reasons.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] It may simply be that the system still provides for the users' needs.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] In addition, the decision to keep an old system may be influenced by economic reasons such as return on investment challenges or vendor lock-in, the inherent challenges of change management, or a variety of other reasons other than functionality.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Backward compatibility (such as the ability of newer systems to handle legacy file formats and character encodings) is a goal that software developers often include in their work.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Even if a legacy system is no longer used, it may continue to impact the organization due to its historical role.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Historic data may not have been converted into the new system format and may exist within the new system with the use of a customized schema crosswalk, or may exist only in a data warehouse.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] In either case, the effect on business intelligence and operational reporting can be significant.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] A legacy system may include procedures or terminology which are no longer relevant in the current context, and may hinder or confuse understanding of the methods or technologies used.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Legacy systems are considered to be potentially problematic by some software engineers for several reasons.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Where it is impossible to replace legacy systems through the practice of application retirement, it is still possible to enhance (or "re-face") them.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Most development often goes into adding new interfaces to a legacy system.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The most prominent technique is to provide a Web-based interface to a terminal-based mainframe application.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] This may reduce staff productivity due to slower response times and slower mouse-based operator actions, yet it is often seen as an "upgrade", because the interface style is familiar to unskilled users and is easy for them to use.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] John McCormick discusses such strategies that involve middleware.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Printing improvements are problematic because legacy software systems often add no formatting instructions, or they use protocols that are not usable in modern PC/Windows printers.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] A print server can be used to intercept the data and translate it to a more modern code.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Rich Text Format (RTF) or PostScript documents may be created in the legacy application and then interpreted at a PC before being printed.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Biometric security measures are difficult to implement on legacy systems.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] A workable solution is to use a Telnet or HTTP proxy server to sit between users and the mainframe to implement secure access to the legacy application.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The change being undertaken in some organizations is to switch to automated business process (ABP) software which generates complete systems.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] These systems can then interface to the organizations' legacy systems and use them as data repositories.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] This approach can provide a number of significant benefits: the users are insulated from the inefficiencies of their legacy systems, and the changes can be incorporated quickly and easily in the ABP software.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Model-driven reverse and forward engineering approaches can be also used for the improvement of legacy software.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Hein researched the use of legacy systems in space exploration at the Technical University of Munich.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] According to Hein, legacy systems are attractive for reuse if an organization has the capabilities for verification, validation, testing, and operational history.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] These capabilities must be integrated into various software life cycle phases such as development, implementation, usage, or maintenance.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] For software systems, the capability to use and maintain the system are crucial.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Otherwise the system will become less and less understandable and maintainable.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] According to Hein, verification, validation, testing, and operational history increases the confidence in a system's reliability and quality.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] However, accumulating this history is often expensive.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] NASA's now retired Space Shuttle program used a large amount of 1970s-era technology.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Replacement was cost-prohibitive because of the expensive requirement for flight certification.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The original hardware completed the expensive integration and certification requirement for flight, but any new equipment would have had to go through that entire process again.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] This long and detailed process required extensive tests of the new components in their new configurations before a single unit could be used in the Space Shuttle program.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Thus any new system that started the certification process becomes a *de facto* legacy system by the time it is approved for flight.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Additionally, the entire Space Shuttle system, including ground and launch vehicle assets, was designed to work together as a closed system.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Since the specifications did not change, all of the certified systems and components performed well in the roles for which they were designed.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Even before the Shuttle was scheduled to be retired in 2010, NASA found it advantageous to keep using many pieces of 1970s technology rather than to upgrade those systems and recertify the new components.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Some in the software engineering prefer to describe "legacy code" without the connotation of being obsolete.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Among the most prevalent neutral conceptions are *source code inherited from someone else* and *source code inherited from an older version of the software*.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Eli Lopian, CEO of Typemock, has defined it as "code that developers are afraid to change".
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Michael Feathers introduced a definition of *legacy code* as *code without tests*, which reflects the perspective of legacy code being difficult to work with in part due to a lack of automated regression tests.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] He also defined characterization tests to start putting *legacy code* under test.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Ginny Hendry characterized creation of code as a "challenge" to current coders to create code that is "like other legacies in our lives—like the antiques, heirlooms, and stories that are cherished and lovingly passed down from one generation to the next.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] What if legacy code was something we took pride in?".
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The term *legacy support* is often used in conjunction with legacy systems.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The term may refer to a feature of modern software.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] For example, operating systems with "legacy support" can detect and use older hardware.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The term may also be used to refer to a business function; e.g. a software or hardware vendor that is supporting, or providing software maintenance, for older products.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] A "legacy" product may be a product that is no longer sold, has lost substantial market share, or is a version of a product that is not current.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] A legacy product may have some advantage over a modern product making it appealing for customers to keep it around.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] A product is only truly "obsolete" if it has an advantage to nobody—if no person making a rational decision would choose to acquire it new.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The term "legacy mode" often refers specifically to backward compatibility.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] A software product that is capable of performing as though it were a previous version of itself, is said to be "running in legacy mode".
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] This kind of feature is common in operating systems and web browsers, where many applications depend on these underlying components.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The computer mainframe era saw many applications running in legacy mode.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] In the modern business computing environment, n-tier, or 3-tier architectures are more difficult to place into legacy mode as they include many components making up a single system.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Virtualization technology is a recent innovation allowing legacy systems to continue to operate on modern hardware by running older operating systems and browsers on a software system that emulates legacy hardware.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Programmers have borrowed the term *brownfield* from the construction industry, where previously developed land (often polluted and abandoned) is described as *brownfield*.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] IT analysts estimate that the cost of replacing business logic is about five times that of reuse, even discounting the risk of system failures and security breaches.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Ideally, businesses would never have to rewrite most core business logic: *debits = credits* is a perennial requirement.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The IT industry is responding with "legacy modernization" and "legacy transformation": refurbishing existing business logic with new user interfaces, sometimes using screen scraping and service-enabled access through web services.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] These techniques allow organizations to understand their existing code assets (using discovery tools), provide new user and application interfaces to existing code, improve workflow, contain costs, minimize risk, and enjoy classic qualities of service (near 100% uptime, security, scalability, etc.).
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] This trend also invites reflection on what makes legacy systems so durable.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Technologists are relearning the importance of sound architecture from the start, to avoid costly and risky rewrites.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] The most common legacy systems tend to be those which embraced well-known IT architectural principles, with careful planning and strict methodology during implementation.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Poorly designed systems often don't last, both because they wear out and because their inherent faults invite replacement.
[src:swe-practice/legacy-system] Thus, many organizations are rediscovering the value of both their legacy systems and the theoretical underpinnings of those systems.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] After 1980, the United States began to treat software as a literary work covered by copyright law.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Richard Stallman founded the free software movement in response to the rise of proprietary software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The term "open source" was used by the Open Source Initiative (OSI), founded by free-software developers Bruce Perens and Eric S.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] "Open source" emphasizes the strengths of the open development model rather than software freedoms.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] While the goals behind the terms are different, open-source licenses and free-software licenses describe the same type of licenses.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The two main categories of open-source licenses are permissive and copyleft.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Both grant permission to change and distribute software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Typically, they require attribution and disclaim liability.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Copyleft licenses come from the free software movement.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Copyleft licenses require derivative works to be distributed with the source code and under a similar license.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Since the mid-2000s, courts in multiple countries have upheld the terms of both types of license.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Software developers have filed cases as copyright infringement and as breaches of contract.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Intellectual property (IP) is a legal category that treats creative output as property, comparable to private property.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Legal systems grant the owner of an IP the right to restrict access in many ways.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Owners can sell, lease, gift, or license their properties.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Multiple types of IP law cover software including trademarks, patents, and copyrights.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Most countries, including the United States (US), have created copyright laws in line with the Berne Convention with slight variations.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] These laws assign a copyright whenever a work is released in any fixed format.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Under US copyright law, the initial release is considered an original work.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The creator, or their employer, holds the copyright to this original work and therefore has the exclusive right to make copies, release modified versions, distribute copies, perform publicly, or display the work publicly.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Modified versions of the original work are derivative works.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] When a creator modifies an existing work, they hold the copyright to their modifications.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Unless the original work was in the public domain, a derivative work can only be distributed with the permission of every copyright holder.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] In 1980, the US government amended the law to treat software as a literary work.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Software released after this point was restricted by IP laws.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] At that time, American activist and programmer Richard Stallman was working as a graduate student at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Stallman witnessed fragmentation among software developers.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] He blamed the spread of proprietary software and closed models of development.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] To push back against these trends, Stallman founded the free software movement.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Throughout the 1980s, he started the GNU Project to create a free operating system, wrote essays on freedom, founded the Free Software Foundation (FSF), and wrote several free-software licenses.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The FSF used existing intellectual property laws for the opposite of their intended goal of restriction.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Instead of imposing restrictions, free software explicitly provided freedoms to the recipient.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] In the 90s, the term "open source" was coined as an alternative label for free software, and specific criteria were laid out to determine which licenses covered free and open-source software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Two active members of the free-software community, Bruce Perens and Eric S.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Raymond, founded the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] At Debian, Perens had proposed the Debian Free Software Guidelines (DFSG).
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The DFSG were drafted to provide a more specific and objective standard for the FOSS that Debian would host in their repositories.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The OSI adopted the DSFG and used them as the basis for their Open Source Definition.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The Free Software Foundation maintains a rival set of criteria, the Free Software Definition.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Historically, these three organizations and their sets of criteria have been the notable authorities in determining whether a license covers free and open-source software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] There is significant diversity among individual licenses but little difference between the rival definitions.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The three definitions each require that people receiving covered software must be able to use, modify, and redistribute the covered work.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Raymond was a proponent of the term "open source" over "free software".
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] He viewed open source as more appealing to businesses and more reflective of the tangible advantages of FOSS development.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] One of Raymond's goals was to expand the existing hacker community to include large commercial developers.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] In *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*, Raymond compared open-source development to the bazaar, an open-air public market.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] He argued that aside from ethics, the open model provided advantages that proprietary software could not replicate.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Raymond focused heavily on feedback, testing, and bug reports.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] He contrasted the proprietary model where small pools of secretive workers carried out this work with the development of Linux where the pool of testers included potentially the entire world.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] He summarized this strength as "Given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow." The OSI succeeded in bringing open-source development to corporate developers including Sun Microsystems, IBM, Netscape, Mozilla, Apache, Apple Inc., Microsoft, and Nokia.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] These companies released code under existing licenses and drafted their own to be approved by the OSI.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Open-source licenses are categorized as copyleft or permissive.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Copyleft licenses require derivative works to include source code under a similar license.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Permissive licenses do not, and therefore the code can be used within proprietary software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Copyleft can be further divided into strong and weak depending on whether they define derivative works broadly or narrowly.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Licenses focus on copyright law, but code is also covered by other forms of IP.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Major open-source licenses written since the late 1990s contain patent grants.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] These open-source patent grants cover the patents held by the developers.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Software patents cover ideas and, rather than a specific implementation, cover *any* implementation of a claim.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Patent claims give the holder the right to exclude others from making, using, selling, or importing products based on the idea.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Because patents grant the right to exclude rather than the right to create, it is possible to have a patent on an idea but still be unable to legally implement it if the invention relies on another patented idea.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Thus, open-source patent grants can offer permission only from covered patents.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] They cannot guarantee that a third party has not patented any concepts embodied in the code.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The older permissive licenses do not discuss patents directly and offer only implicit patent grants in their offers to use or sell covered material.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Newer copyleft licenses and the 2004 Apache License offer explicit patent grants and limited protection from patent litigation.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] These patent retaliation clauses protect developers by terminating grants for any party who initiates a patent lawsuit regarding covered software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Trademarks are the only form of IP not shared by free and open-source software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Trademarks on FOSS function the same as any other trademark.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] A trademark is a design that identifies the distinct source of a product.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Because they distinguish products, the same designs can be used in different fields where there is no risk of confusing similar sources.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] To give up control of a trademark would result in the loss of that trademark.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Therefore, no open-source license freely offers the use of a trademark.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Trademark restrictions can overlap copyrights and affect material otherwise freely available.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The US Supreme Court described using trademark law to restrict public domain content as "mutant copyright".
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Twentieth Century Fox Film Corp.*, the court "caution[ed] against misuse or over-extension of trademark" law without providing a firm decision on those mutant copyrights.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Trademark overlap can leave open-source and free content projects vulnerable to a "hostile takeover" if outside parties file for trademarks on derivative works.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Notably, Andrey Duskin applied for trademarks on the SCP Foundation, a collaborative writing project, when creating derivative works based on SCP stories.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Permissive licenses, also known as academic licenses, allow recipients to use, modify, and distribute software with no obligation to provide source code.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Institutions created these licenses to distribute their creations to the public.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Permissive licenses are usually short, often less than a page of text.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Most include disclaimers of warranty and obligations to credit authors.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] A few include explicit provisions for patents, trademarks, and other forms of intellectual property.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The University of California, Berkeley created the first open-source license when they began distributing their Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) operating system.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The BSD license and its later variations permit modification and distribution of the covered software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The licenses brought the concept of academic freedom of ideas to computing.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Early academic software authors had shared code based on implied promises.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Berkeley made these concepts explicit with clear disclaimers for liability and warranty along with conditions, or clauses, for redistribution.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The original had four clauses, but subsequent versions have further reduced the restrictions.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] As a result, it is common to specify if the covered software uses a 2-clause or 3-clause version.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) created an academic license based on the BSD original.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The MIT license clarified the conditions by making them more explicit.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] For example, the MIT license describes the right to sublicense.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] One of the strengths of open-source development is the continual process where developers can build on the derivative works of each other and combine their projects into collective works.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Explicitly making covered code sublicensable provides a legal advantage when tracking the chain of authorship.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The BSD and MIT are template licenses that can be adapted to any project.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] They are widely adapted and used by many FOSS projects.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The Apache License is more comprehensive and explicit.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The Apache Software Foundation wrote it for their Apache HTTP Server.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Version 2, published in 2004, offers legal advantages over simple licenses and provides similar grants.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] While the BSD and MIT licenses offer an implicit patent grant, the Apache License includes a section on patents with an explicit grant from contributors.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Additionally, it is one of the few permissive licenses with a patent retaliation clause.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Patent retaliation, or patent suspension, clauses take effect if a licensee initiates patent infringement litigation on covered code.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] In that situation, the patent grants are revoked.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] These clauses protect against patent trolling.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Copyleft licenses require source code to be distributed with software and require the source code to be made available under a similar license.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Like the permissive licenses, most copyleft licenses require attribution.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Most, including the GPL, disclaim implied warranties.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Copyleft uses the restrictions of IP law—contrary to their usual purpose—to mandate that the code remain open.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The term and its related slogan, "All rights reversed", had been previously used in a playful manner by the *Principia Discordia* and Tiny BASIC; the modern usage begins with Richard Stallman's efforts to create a free operating system.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] In 1984, programmer Don Hopkins mailed a manual to Stallman with a "Copyleft Ⓛ" sticker.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Stallman, who was working on the GNU operating system, adopted the term.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] An early version of copyleft licensing was used for the 1985 release of GNU Emacs.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The term became associated with the FSF's later reciprocal licenses, notably the GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Traditional, proprietary software licenses are written with the goal of increasing profit, but Stallman wrote the GPL to increase the body of available free software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] His reciprocal licenses offer the rights to use, modify, and distribute the work on the condition that people must release derivative works under a license offering these same freedoms.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Software built on a copyleft base must come with the source code, and the source code must be available under the same or a similar license.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] This offers protection against proprietary software consuming code without giving back.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The separate terms free software and open-source software reflect different values rather than a legal difference.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Both movements and their formal definitions require the covered work to be made available with source code and with permission for modification and redistribution.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] There are occasional edge cases where only one of the FSF or the OSI accept a license, but the popular free-software licenses are open source, including the GPL.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Practical benefits to copyleft licenses have attracted commercial developers.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Corporations have used and written reciprocal licenses with a narrower scope than the GPL.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] For example, Netscape drafted their own copyleft terms after rejecting permissive licenses for the Mozilla project.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The GPL remains the most popular license of this type, but there are other significant examples.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The FSF has crafted the Lesser General Public License (LGPL) for libraries.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Mozilla uses the Mozilla Public License (MPL) for their releases, including Firefox.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] IBM drafted the Common Public License (CPL) and later adopted the Eclipse Public License (EPL).
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] A difference between the GPL and other reciprocal licenses is how they define derivative works covered by the reciprocal provisions.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The GPL, and the Affero License (AGPL) based on it, use a broad scope to describe affected works.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The AGPL extends the reciprocal obligation in the GPL to cover software made available over a network.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] They are called strong copyleft in contrast to the weaker copyleft licenses often used by corporations.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Weak copyleft uses narrower, explicit definitions of derivative works.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The MPL uses a file-based definition, the CPL and EPL use a module-based definition, and the FSF's own LGPL refers to software libraries.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] License compatibility determines how code with different licenses can be distributed together.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The goal of open-source licensing is to make the work freely available, but this becomes complicated when working with multiple terminologies imposing different requirements.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] There are many uncommonly used licenses and some projects write their own bespoke agreements.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] As a result, this causes more confusion than other legal aspects.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] When releasing a collection of applications, each license can be considered separately.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] However, when attempting to combine software, code from another project can only be in-licensed if the project uses compatible terms and conditions.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] When combining code bases, the original licenses can be maintained for separate components, and the larger work released under a compatible license.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Public domain content can be used anywhere as there is no copyright claim, but code acquired under any almost any set of terms cannot be waved to the public domain.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Permissive licenses can be used within copyleft works, but copyleft material cannot be released under a permissive license.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Some weak copyleft licenses can be used under the GPL and are said to be GPL-compatible.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] GPL software can only be used under the GPL or AGPL.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Permissive licenses are broadly compatible because they can cover separate parts of a project.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Multiple licenses including the GPL and Apache License have been revised to enhance compatibility.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Translation issues, ambiguity in licensing terms, and incompatibility of some licenses with the law in certain jurisdictions compound the problem of license compatibility.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Downloading an open-source module is straightforward, but complying with the licensing terms can be more difficult.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Because of the amount of software dependencies, engineers working on complex projects often rely on license management software to achieve compliance with the licensing terms of open-source components.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Many open-source software files do not unambiguously state the license, increasing the difficulties of compliance.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Free and open-source software licenses have been successfully enforced in civil court since the mid-2000s.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Katzer in the United States and Welte v.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Sitecom in Germany—defendants argued that open-source licenses were invalid.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Sitecom and Katzer separately argued that the licenses were unenforceable.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Both the US and German courts rejected these claims.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] They ruled that the defendants could not have legally distributed the software if the licenses were unenforceable.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Courts have found that distributing software indicates acceptance of the license's terms.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Physical software releases can obtain the consumer's assent with notices placed on shrinkwrap.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Online distribution can use clickwrap, a digital equivalent where the user must click to accept.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Open-source software has an additional acceptance mechanism.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Without permission from the copyright holder, the law prohibits redistribution.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Therefore, courts treat redistribution as acceptance of the license terms.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] These can include attribution provisions or source code provisions for copyleft licenses.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Developers typically achieve compliance without lawsuits.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Social pressures, like the potential for community backlash, are often sufficient.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Cease and desist letters are a common method to bring companies back into compliance, especially in Germany.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] A standard process has developed in the German legal system.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] FOSS developers present companies with a cease and desist letter.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] These letters outline how to come back into compliance from a violation.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] German judges can issue a court-mandated cease and desist order to unresponsive companies.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Civil cases proceed if these first steps fail.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The German procedural laws are clear and favorable to claimants.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Uncertainties remain in how different courts will handle certain aspects of licensing.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] For software in general, there are debates about what can be patented and what can be copyrighted.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Regarding an application programming interface (API), the European Court of Justice noted in the 2012 *SAS Institute* case that "ideas and principles which underlie [computer program] interfaces are not protected by copyright".
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] In a similar 2021 case, the US Supreme Court permitted the recreation of an API in a transformative product under fair use.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] A long-debated subject within the FOSS community is whether open-source licenses are "bare licenses" or contracts.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] A bare license is a set of conditions under which actions otherwise restricted by IP laws are permitted.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Under the bare license interpretation, advocated by the FSF, a case is brought to court by the copyright holder as copyright infringement.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Under the contract interpretation, a case can be brought to court by an involved party as a breach of contract.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] US and French courts have tried cases under both interpretations.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Non-profit organizations like FSF and the Software Freedom Conservancy offer to hold the rights to developers' projects to enforce compliance.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] When a copyright expires, the work enters the public domain, and is freely available to anyone.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Some creative works are not covered by copyright and enter directly into the public domain.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] In the early history of computing, this applied to software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Early computer software was often given away with hardware.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Developed initially at MIT, the pioneering video game Spacewar! was used to market and test the PDP-1 computer.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] According to attorney Lawrence Rosen, copyright laws were not written with the expectation that creators would place their work into the public domain.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Thus intellectual property laws lack clear paths to waive a copyright.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Highly permissive licenses described as "public domain" may legally function as unilateral contracts that offer something but impose no terms.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] A public-domain-equivalent license, like the Creative Commons CC0, provides a waiver of copyright claims into the public domain along with a permissive software license as a fallback.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] In jurisdictions that do not accept a public domain waiver, the permissive license takes effect.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Public domain waivers share limitations with simple academic licenses.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] This creates the possibility that an outside party could attempt to control a public domain work via patent or trademark law.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Public domain waivers handle warranties differently from any type of license.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Even very permissive ones, like the MIT license, disclaim warranty and liability.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Anyone using the free software must accept this disclaimer as a condition.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Because public domain content is available to everyone, the copyright waiver cannot impose a disclaimer.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Open-source licenses allow other businesses to commercialize covered software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Work released under a permissive license can be incorporated into proprietary software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Permissive licenses permit the addition of new terms, including proprietary ones.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Proprietary software has heavily integrated open-source code released under the Apache, BSD, and MIT licenses.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Open core is a business model where developers release a core piece of software as open source and monetize a product containing it as proprietary software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The strong copyleft GPL is written to prevent distribution within proprietary software.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Weak copyleft licenses impose specific requirements on derivative works that may allow the covered code to be distributed within proprietary software in certain circumstances.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Cloud computing relies on free and open-source software and avoids the distribution that triggers most licenses.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Cloud software is hosted rather than distributed.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] A vendor hosts the software online, and their end users do not have to download, access, or even know about the code in use.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] The copyleft GNU Affero General Public License (AGPL) is triggered when covered code is hosted or distributed.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Some developers have adopted the AGPL, and others have switched to proprietary licenses with features of open-source licensing.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] For example, open-core developer Elastic switched from the Apache license to the "source-available" Server Side Public License.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Source-available software comes with source code as a reference.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Since 2010, the cloud model has grown in prominence.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Developers have criticized cloud companies that profit from hosting open-source software without contributing money or code upstream, comparing the practice to strip mining.
[src:swe-practice/open-source-license] Cloud computing leader Amazon Web Services has stated they comply with licenses and act in their customers' best interests.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Additional labels for pre-release and build metadata are available as extensions to the MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH format.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] In the world of software management there exists a dreaded place called “dependency hell.” The bigger your system grows and the more packages you integrate into your software, the more likely you are to find yourself, one day, in this pit of despair.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] In systems with many dependencies, releasing new package versions can quickly become a nightmare.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If the dependency specifications are too tight, you are in danger of version lock (the inability to upgrade a package without having to release new versions of every dependent package).
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If dependencies are specified too loosely, you will inevitably be bitten by version promiscuity (assuming compatibility with more future versions than is reasonable).
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Dependency hell is where you are when version lock and/or version promiscuity prevent you from easily and safely moving your project forward.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] As a solution to this problem, we propose a simple set of rules and requirements that dictate how version numbers are assigned and incremented.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] These rules are based on but not necessarily limited to pre-existing widespread common practices in use in both closed and open-source software.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] For this system to work, you first need to declare a public API.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] This may consist of documentation or be enforced by the code itself.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Regardless, it is important that this API be clear and precise.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Once you identify your public API, you communicate changes to it with specific increments to your version number.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Consider a version format of X.Y.Z (Major.Minor.Patch).
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Bug fixes not affecting the API increment the patch version, backward compatible API additions/changes increment the minor version, and backward incompatible API changes increment the major version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] We call this system “Semantic Versioning.” Under this scheme, version numbers and the way they change convey meaning about the underlying code and what has been modified from one version to the next.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] The key words “MUST”, “MUST NOT”, “REQUIRED”, “SHALL”, “SHALL NOT”, “SHOULD”, “SHOULD NOT”, “RECOMMENDED”, “MAY”, and “OPTIONAL” in this document are to be interpreted as described in RFC 2119.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] A normal version number MUST take the form X.Y.Z where X, Y, and Z are non-negative integers, and MUST NOT contain leading zeroes.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] X is the major version, Y is the minor version, and Z is the patch version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Once a versioned package has been released, the contents of that version MUST NOT be modified.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Any modifications MUST be released as a new version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Major version zero (0.y.z) is for initial development.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] The public API SHOULD NOT be considered stable.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] The way in which the version number is incremented after this release is dependent on this public API and how it changes.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Patch version Z (x.y.Z | x > 0) MUST be incremented if only backward compatible bug fixes are introduced.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] A bug fix is defined as an internal change that fixes incorrect behavior.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Minor version Y (x.Y.z | x > 0) MUST be incremented if new, backward compatible functionality is introduced to the public API.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] It MUST be incremented if any public API functionality is marked as deprecated.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] It MAY be incremented if substantial new functionality or improvements are introduced within the private code.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Patch version MUST be reset to 0 when minor version is incremented.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Major version X (X.y.z | X > 0) MUST be incremented if any backward incompatible changes are introduced to the public API.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] It MAY also include minor and patch level changes.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Patch and minor versions MUST be reset to 0 when major version is incremented.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] A pre-release version MAY be denoted by appending a hyphen and a series of dot separated identifiers immediately following the patch version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Identifiers MUST comprise only ASCII alphanumerics and hyphens [0-9A-Za-z-].
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Numeric identifiers MUST NOT include leading zeroes.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Pre-release versions have a lower precedence than the associated normal version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] A pre-release version indicates that the version is unstable and might not satisfy the intended compatibility requirements as denoted by its associated normal version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Build metadata MAY be denoted by appending a plus sign and a series of dot separated identifiers immediately following the patch or pre-release version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Build metadata MUST be ignored when determining version precedence.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Thus two versions that differ only in the build metadata, have the same precedence.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Precedence refers to how versions are compared to each other when ordered.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Precedence is determined by the first difference when comparing each of these identifiers from left to right as follows: Major, minor, and patch versions are always compared numerically.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] When major, minor, and patch are equal, a pre-release version has lower precedence than a normal version: Example: 1.0.0-alpha < 1.0.0.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Identifiers with letters or hyphens are compared lexically in ASCII sort order.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Numeric identifiers always have lower precedence than non-numeric identifiers.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] A larger set of pre-release fields has a higher precedence than a smaller set, if all of the preceding identifiers are equal.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] This is not a new or revolutionary idea.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] In fact, you probably do something close to this already.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] The problem is that “close” isn’t good enough.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Without compliance to some sort of formal specification, version numbers are essentially useless for dependency management.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] By giving a name and clear definition to the above ideas, it becomes easy to communicate your intentions to the users of your software.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Once these intentions are clear, flexible (but not too flexible) dependency specifications can finally be made.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] A simple example will demonstrate how Semantic Versioning can make dependency hell a thing of the past.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Consider a library called “Firetruck.” It requires a Semantically Versioned package named “Ladder.” At the time that Firetruck is created, Ladder is at version 3.1.0.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Since Firetruck uses some functionality that was first introduced in 3.1.0, you can safely specify the Ladder dependency as greater than or equal to 3.1.0 but less than 4.0.0.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Now, when Ladder version 3.1.1 and 3.2.0 become available, you can release them to your package management system and know that they will be compatible with existing dependent software.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] As a responsible developer you will, of course, want to verify that any package upgrades function as advertised.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] The real world is a messy place; there’s nothing we can do about that but be vigilant.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] What you can do is let Semantic Versioning provide you with a sane way to release and upgrade packages without having to roll new versions of dependent packages, saving you time and hassle.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If all of this sounds desirable, all you need to do to start using Semantic Versioning is to declare that you are doing so and then follow the rules.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Link to this website from your README so others know the rules and can benefit from them.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] The simplest thing to do is start your initial development release at 0.1.0 and then increment the minor version for each subsequent release.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If your software is being used in production, it should probably already be 1.0.0.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If you have a stable API on which users have come to depend, you should be 1.0.0.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If you’re worrying a lot about backward compatibility, you should probably already be 1.0.0.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Major version zero is all about rapid development.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If you’re changing the API every day you should either still be in version 0.y.z or on a separate development branch working on the next major version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] This is a question of responsible development and foresight.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Incompatible changes should not be introduced lightly to software that has a lot of dependent code.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] The cost that must be incurred to upgrade can be significant.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Having to bump major versions to release incompatible changes means you’ll think through the impact of your changes, and evaluate the cost/benefit ratio involved.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] It is your responsibility as a professional developer to properly document software that is intended for use by others.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Managing software complexity is a hugely important part of keeping a project efficient, and that’s hard to do if nobody knows how to use your software, or what methods are safe to call.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] In the long run, Semantic Versioning, and the insistence on a well defined public API can keep everyone and everything running smoothly.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] As soon as you realize that you’ve broken the Semantic Versioning spec, fix the problem and release a new minor version that corrects the problem and restores backward compatibility.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Even under this circumstance, it is unacceptable to modify versioned releases.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If it’s appropriate, document the offending version and inform your users of the problem so that they are aware of the offending version.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] That would be considered compatible since it does not affect the public API.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Software that explicitly depends on the same dependencies as your package should have their own dependency specifications and the author will notice any conflicts.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Determining whether the change is a patch level or minor level modification depends on whether you updated your dependencies in order to fix a bug or introduce new functionality.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] We would usually expect additional code for the latter instance, in which case it’s obviously a minor level increment.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If you have a huge audience that will be drastically impacted by changing the behavior back to what the public API intended, then it may be best to perform a major version release, even though the fix could strictly be considered a patch release.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Remember, Semantic Versioning is all about conveying meaning by how the version number changes.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If these changes are important to your users, use the version number to inform them.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Deprecating existing functionality is a normal part of software development and is often required to make forward progress.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] When you deprecate part of your public API, you should do two things: (1) update your documentation to let users know about the change, (2) issue a new minor release with the deprecation in place.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Before you completely remove the functionality in a new major release there should be at least one minor release that contains the deprecation so that users can smoothly transition to the new API.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] A 255 character version string is probably overkill, for example.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Also, specific systems may impose their own limits on the size of the string.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] However, prefixing a semantic version with a “v” is a common way (in English) to indicate it is a version number.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Abbreviating “version” as “v” is often seen with version control.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] Example: `git tag v1.2.3 -m "Release version 1.2.3"`, in which case “v1.2.3” is a tag name and the semantic version is “1.2.3”.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] One with named groups for those systems that support them (PCRE [Perl Compatible Regular Expressions, i.e.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] And one with numbered capture groups instead (so cg1 = major, cg2 = minor, cg3 = patch, cg4 = prerelease and cg5 = buildmetadata) that is compatible with ECMA Script (JavaScript), PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expressions, i.e.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] The Semantic Versioning specification was originally authored by Tom Preston-Werner, inventor of Gravatar and cofounder of GitHub.
[src:swe-practice/semver-org] If you’d like to leave feedback, please open an issue on GitHub.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] and transfer to the computer system(s) on which it will be run in production.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] required for the system to operate with tolerable performance and planning and/or documenting subsequent activities of the deployment process.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] for executing the software (manually or automatically).
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] and/or making all the required subsystems ready to use.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] , the main copy of the software to be used by users - "production" - might be installed on a production server in a production environment.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:swe-practice/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Documentation is an important part of software engineering.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Requirements documentation is the description of what a given software does or should do.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is used throughout development to communicate how the software functions or how it is intended to operate.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is also used as an agreement or as the foundation for agreement on what the software will do.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Requirements are produced and consumed by everyone involved in the production of software, including: end users, customers, project managers, sales, marketing, software architects, usability engineers, interaction designers, developers, and testers.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Requirements come in a variety of styles, notations and formality.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Requirements can be goal-like (e.g., *distributed work environment*), close to design (e.g., *builds can be started by right-clicking a configuration file and selecting the 'build' function*), and anything in between.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] They can be specified as statements in natural language, as drawn figures, as detailed mathematical formulas, or as a combination of them all.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The variation and complexity of requirement documentation make it a proven challenge.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Requirements may be implicit and hard to uncover.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is difficult to know exactly how much and what kind of documentation is needed and how much can be left to the architecture and design documentation, and it is difficult to know how to document requirements considering the variety of people who shall read and use the documentation.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Thus, requirements documentation is often incomplete (or non-existent).
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Without proper requirements documentation, software changes become more difficult — and therefore more error prone (decreased software quality) and time-consuming (expensive).
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The need for requirements documentation is typically related to the complexity of the product, the impact of the product, and the life expectancy of the software.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] If the software is very complex or developed by many people (e.g., mobile phone software), requirements can help better communicate what to achieve.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] If the software is safety-critical and can have a negative impact on human life (e.g., nuclear power systems, medical equipment, mechanical equipment), more formal requirements documentation is often required.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] If the software is expected to live for only a month or two (e.g., very small mobile phone applications developed specifically for a certain campaign) very little requirements documentation may be needed.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] If the software is a first release that is later built upon, requirements documentation is very helpful when managing the change of the software and verifying that nothing has been broken in the software when it is modified.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Traditionally, requirements are specified in requirements documents (e.g. using word processing applications and spreadsheet applications).
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] To manage the increased complexity and changing nature of requirements documentation (and software documentation in general), database-centric systems and special-purpose requirements management tools are advocated.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] In Agile software development, requirements are often expressed as *user stories* with accompanying acceptance criteria.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] User stories are typically part of a feature, or an epic, which is a broader functionality or set of related functionalities that deliver a specific value to the user based on the business requirements.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Architecture documentation (also known as software architecture description) is a special type of design document.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] In a way, architecture documents are third derivative from the code (design document being second derivative, and code documents being first).
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Very little in the architecture documents is specific to the code.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] These documents do not describe how to program a given routine, or even why a routine exists in the form that it does, but instead merely list the general requirements that would motivate the existence of such a routine.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] A good architecture document is short on details but thick on explanation.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It may suggest approaches for lower level design, but leave the actual exploration trade studies to other documents.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Another type of design document is the comparison document, or trade study.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] This would often take the form of a *whitepaper*.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It focuses on one specific aspect of the system and suggests alternate approaches.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It could be at the user interface, code, design, or even architectural level.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It will outline what the situation is, describe one or more alternatives, and enumerate the pros and cons of each.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] A good trade study document is heavy on research, expresses its idea clearly (without relying heavily on obtuse jargon to dazzle the reader), and most importantly is impartial.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It should honestly and clearly explain the costs of whatever solution it offers as best.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The objective of a trade study is to devise the best solution, rather than to advance some viewpoint.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is acceptable to state no conclusion, or to conclude that none of the alternatives are sufficiently better than the baseline to warrant a change.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It should be approached as a scientific endeavor, not as a marketing technique.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] A very important part of the design document in enterprise software development is the Database Design Document (DDD).
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It contains Conceptual, Logical, and Physical Design Elements.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The DDD includes the formal information that the people who interact with the database need.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The purpose of preparing it is to create a common source to be used by all players within the scene.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is very important to include all information that is to be used by all actors in the scene.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is also very important to update the documents as any change occurs in the database as well.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is important for the code documents associated with the source code (which may include README files and application programming interface (API) documentation) to be thorough, but not so verbose that it becomes overly time-consuming or difficult to maintain them.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Various how-to and overview documentation guides are commonly found specific to the software application or software product being documented by API writers.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] This documentation may be used by developers, testers, and also end-users.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Today, a lot of high-end applications are seen in the fields of power, energy, transportation, networks, aerospace, safety, security, industry automation, and a variety of other domains.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Technical documentation has become important within such organizations as the basic and advanced level of information may change over a period of time with architecture changes.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] There is evidence that the existence of good code documentation actually reduces maintenance costs for software.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Code documents are often organized into a *reference guide* style, allowing a programmer to quickly look up an arbitrary function or class.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The idea of auto-generating documentation is attractive to programmers for various reasons.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] For example, because it is extracted from the source code (for example, through comments), the programmer can write it while referring to the code, and use the same tools used to create the source code to make the documentation.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] This makes it much easier to keep the documentation up-to-date.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] A possible downside is that only programmers can edit this kind of documentation, and it depends on them to refresh the output (for example, by running a cron job to update the documents nightly).
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Some would characterize this as a pro rather than a con.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Respected computer scientist Donald Knuth has noted that documentation can be a very difficult afterthought process and has advocated literate programming (LP), written at the same time and location as the source code and extracted by automatic means.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The programming languages Haskell and CoffeeScript have built-in support for a simple form of LP, but this support is not used widely.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Elucidative programming is the result of practical applications of literate programming in real programming contexts.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The elucidative paradigm proposes that source code and documentation be stored separately.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Often, software developers need to be able to create and access information that is not going to be part of the source file itself.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Such annotations are usually part of several software development activities, such as code walks and porting, where third-party source code is analysed in a functional way.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Annotations can therefore help the developer during any stage of software development where a formal documentation system would hinder progress.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Unlike code documents, user documents simply describe how a program is used.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] In the case of a software library, the code documents and user documents could in some cases be effectively equivalent and worth conjoining, but for a general application this is not often true.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Typically, the user documentation describes each feature of the program, and assists the user in realizing these features.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is very important for user documents to not be confusing, and for them to be up to date.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] User documents do not need to be organized in any given way, but it is very important for them to have a thorough index.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Consistency and simplicity are also very valuable.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] User documentation is considered to constitute a contract specifying what the software will do.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] API Writers are very well accomplished towards writing good user documents as they would be well aware of the software architecture and programming techniques used.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] User documentation can be produced in a variety of online and print formats.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] *Thematic* – A thematic approach, where chapters or sections concentrate on one given area of interest, is of more general use to an intermediate user.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Some authors prefer to convey ideas through a knowledge based article to facilitate the user needs.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] This approach is usually practiced by a dynamic industry, such as Information technology.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] *List or Reference* – The final type of organizing principle is one in which commands or tasks are simply listed alphabetically or logically grouped, often via cross-referenced indexes.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] This latter approach is of greater use to advanced users who know exactly what sort of information they are looking for.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] A common complaint among users regarding software documentation is that only one of these three approaches was taken to the near-exclusion of the other two.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] It is common to limit provided software documentation for personal computers to online help that gives only reference information on commands or menu items.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The job of tutoring new users or helping more experienced users get the most out of a program is left to private publishers, who are often given significant assistance by the software developer.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Like other forms of technical documentation, good user documentation benefits from an organized process of development.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Planning, or the actual documentation phase.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Draft review, is a self-explanatory phase where feedback is sought on the draft composed in the previous step.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Usability testing, whereby the usability of the document is tested empirically.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Editing, is the final step in which the information collected in steps three and four is used to produce the final draft.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] For many applications it is necessary to have some promotional materials to encourage casual observers to spend more time learning about the product.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] To inform them about what exactly the product does, so that their expectations are in line with what they will be receiving.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] To explain the position of this product with respect to other alternatives.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] "The resistance to documentation among developers is well known and needs no emphasis." This situation is common in agile software development because those methodologies try to avoid needless activities that add no direct value.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] The Agile Manifesto advocates valuing "working software over comprehensive documentation", which could be interpreted cynically as "We want to spend all our time coding.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] A survey among software engineering experts revealed, however, that documentation is by no means considered unnecessary in agile development.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Yet it is acknowledged that there are motivational problems in development, and that documentation methods tailored to agile development (e.g. through Reputation systems and Gamification) may be needed.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Combining Docs as Code with Agile methods creates a robust framework for maintaining high-quality, up-to-date documentation.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] *Automate Processes* – Implement CI/CD tools to automate generating and deploying documentation.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] *Define Roles* – Assign roles and responsibilities for documentation within the Agile team.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] Ensure everyone understands the importance of documentation.
[src:swe-practice/software-documentation] *Regular Reviews* – Schedule regular documentation reviews as part of the sprint retrospectives.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] A **software license** is a legal instrument governing the use or redistribution of software.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Since the 1970s, software copyright has been recognized in the United States.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Despite the copyright being recognized, most companies prefer to sell licenses rather than copies of the software because it enables them to enforce stricter terms on redistribution.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Very few purchasers read any part of the license, initially shrink-wrap contracts and now most commonly encountered as clickwrap or browsewrap.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The enforceability of this kind of license is a matter of controversy and is limited in some jurisdictions.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Service-level agreements are another type of software license where the vendor agrees to provide a level of service to the purchaser, often backed by financial penalties.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Copyleft is a type of license that mandates derivative works to be licensed under the license's terms.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Copyleft licenses are free and open source licenses.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Attempts have been made to describe licenses which do not uphold the Four Freedoms, such as the Server Side Public License and others, as "copyleft", but this is widely rejected as an abuse of the term.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The other types of free licenses lack this requirement: for permissive licenses, attribution is typically the only requirement, and public-domain-equivalent licenses have no restrictions.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The source code (or compiled binaries in the form of object code) of a computer program is protected by copyright law that vests the owner with the exclusive right to copy the code.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The underlying ideas or algorithms are not protected by copyright law, but are often treated as a trade secret and concealed by such methods as non-disclosure agreements.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Software copyright has been recognized since the mid-1970s and is vested in the company that makes the software, not the employees or contractors who wrote it.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The tendency to license proprietary software, rather than sell it, dates from the time period before the existence, then the scope of software copyright protection was clear.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] These licenses have continued in use after software copyright was recognized in the courts, and are considered to grant the company extra protection compared to copyright law.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] According to United States federal law, a company can restrict the parties to which it sells but it cannot prevent a buyer from reselling the product.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Software licensing agreements usually prohibit resale, enabling the company to maximize revenue.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Traditionally, software was distributed in the form of binary object code that could not be understood or modified by the user, but could be downloaded and run.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The user bought a perpetual license to use a particular version of the software.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Software as service (SaaS) vendors—who have the majority market share in application software as of 2023—rarely offer perpetual licenses.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] SaaS licenses are usually temporary and charged on a pay-per-usage or subscription basis, although other revenue models such as freemium are also used.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] For customers, the advantages of temporary licenses include reduced upfront cost, increased flexibility, and lower overall cost compared to a perpetual license.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] In some cases, the steep one-time cost demanded by sellers of traditional software were out of the reach of smaller businesses, but pay-per-use SaaS models makes the software affordable.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Initially, end-user license agreements (EULAs) were printed on either the shrinkwrap packaging encasing the product (see shrink-wrap contract) or a piece of paper.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The license often stipulated that a customer agreed if they did not return the product within a specified interval.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] More recently, EULAs are most commonly found as clickwrap or browsewrap where the user's clicks or continued browsing are taken as a sign of agreement.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] As a result of the end of physical constraints, length increased.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Most EULAs have been designed so that it is very difficult to read and understand them, but easy to agree to the licensing terms without reading them.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Regardless of how easy it is to access, very few consumers read any part of the license agreement.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Most assume the terms are unobjectionable or barely notice agreeing while installing the software.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Companies take advantage of consumers' inattention to insert provisions into EULAs.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Proprietary software is usually offered under a restrictive license that bans copying and reuse and often limits the purchaser to using the software on one computer.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Derivative software works and reverse engineering are usually explicitly prohibited.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Many EULAs allow the vendor to collect information about the user and use it in unrestricted ways.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Some EULAs restrict the ability of users to exercise copyright over derivative work made using the software, such as creative creations in the virtual worlds of video games.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Most disclaim any liability for harms caused by the product, and prevent the purchaser from accessing the court system to seek a remedy.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Furthermore, many EULAs allow the vendor to change the terms at any time and the customer must choose between agreeing or ceasing use of the product, without getting a refund.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] It is common for EULAs to allow unilateral termination by the vendor for any number of vague reasons or none at all.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] EULAs, almost always offered on a take-it-or-leave-it basis as a non-negotiable condition for using the software, are very far from the prototypical contract where both parties fully understand the terms and agree of their own free will.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] There has been substantial debate on to what extent the agreements can be considered binding.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Before 1996 in the United States, clickwrap or browsewrap licenses were not held to be binding, but since then they often have been.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Under the New Digital Content Directive effective in the European Union, EULAs are only enforceable to the extent that they do not breach reasonable consumer expectations.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The gap between expectations and the content of EULAs is especially wide when it comes to restrictions on copying and transferring ownership of digital content.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Many EULAs contain stipulations that are likely unenforceable depending on the jurisdiction.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Software vendors keep these unenforceable provisions in the agreements, perhaps because users rarely resort to the legal system to challenge them.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Service-level agreements are often used for enterprise software and guarantee a level of service, such as software performance or time to respond to issue raised by the customer.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Many stipulate financial penalties if the service falls short of the agreed standard.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] SLAs often cover such aspects as availability, reliability, price, and security using quantifiable metrics.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Multi-tier SLAs are common in cloud computing because of the use of different computing services that may be managed by different companies.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] SLAs in cloud computing are an area under active research as of 2024.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Before the open-source movement in the 1980s, almost all software was proprietary and did not disclose its source code.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Open-source licensing is intended to maximize openness and minimize barriers to software use, dissemination, and follow-on innovation.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The Open Source Initiative vets and approves new open-source licenses that comply with its Open Source Definition.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Outside of software, noncommercial-only Creative Commons licenses have become popular among some artists who wish to prevent others from profiting excessively from their work.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] However, software that is made available for noncommercial use only is not considered open source.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Sun Microsystems' noncommercial-only Java Research License was rejected by the open-source community, and in 2006 the company released most of Java under the GPL.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Since 1989, a variety of open-source licenses for software have been created.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Choosing an open-source software license has grown increasingly difficult due to the proliferation of licenses, many of which are only trivially distinct.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Many licenses are incompatible with each other, hampering the goals of the free software movement.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Translation issues, ambiguity in licensing terms, and incompatibility of some licenses with the law in certain jurisdictions compounds the problem.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Although downloading an open-source module is quick and easy, complying with the licensing terms can be more difficult.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The amount of software dependencies means that engineers working on complex projects must often rely on software license management software in order to help them achieve compliance with the licensing terms of open-source components.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Public domain content can be used anywhere as there is no copyright claim, but code acquired under almost any set of terms cannot be waved to the public domain.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] However, developers typically achieve compliance without lawsuits.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Social pressures, such as the potential for community backlash, are often sufficient.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] A bare license is a set of conditions under which actions otherwise restricted by intellectual property laws are permitted.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Under the bare license interpretation, advocated by the Free Software Foundation (FSF), a case is brought to court by the copyright holder as copyright infringement.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] United States and French courts have tried cases under both interpretations.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] More than 90 percent of companies use open-source software as a component of their proprietary software.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] The decision to use open-source software, or even engage with open-source projects to improve existing open-source software, is typically a pragmatic business decision.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] When proprietary software is in direct competition with an open-source alternative, research has found conflicting results on the effect of the competition on the proprietary product's price and quality.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] For decades, some companies have made servicing of an open-source software product for enterprise users as their business model.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] These companies control an open-source software product, and instead of charging for licensing or use, charge for improvements, integration, and other servicing.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Software as a service (SaaS) products based on open-source components are increasingly common.
[src:swe-practice/software-license] Open-source software is preferred for scientific applications, because it increases transparency and aids in the validation and acceptance of scientific results.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Software maintenance is often considered lower skilled and less rewarding than new development.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] As such, it is a common target for outsourcing or offshoring.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Usually, the team developing the software is different from those who will be maintaining it.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The developers lack an incentive to write the code to be easily maintained.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Software is often delivered incomplete and almost always contains some bugs that the maintenance team must fix.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Software maintenance often initially includes the development of new functionality, but as the product nears the end of its lifespan, maintenance is reduced to the bare minimum and then cut off entirely before the product is withdrawn.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Each maintenance cycle begins with a change request typically originating from an end user.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] That request is evaluated and if it is decided to implement it, the programmer studies the existing code to understand how it works before implementing the change.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Testing to make sure the existing functionality is retained and the desired new functionality is added often comprises most of the maintenance cost.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Software maintenance is not as well studied as other phases of the software life cycle, despite comprising most of the cost.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Understanding has not changed significantly since the 1980s.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Software maintenance can be categorized into several types depending on whether it is preventative or reactive and whether it is seeking to add functionality or preserve existing functionality, the latter typically in the face of a changed environment.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] In the early 1970s, companies began to separate out software maintenance with its own team of engineers to free up software development teams from support tasks.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Canning published "The Maintenance 'Iceberg'", in which he contended that software maintenance was an extension of software development with an additional input: the existing system.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The discipline of software maintenance has changed little since then.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] One twenty-first century innovation has been companies deliberately releasing incomplete software and planning to finish it post-release.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] This type of change, and others that expand functionality, is often called software evolution instead of maintenance.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Despite testing and quality assurance, virtually all software contains bugs where the system does not work as intended.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Post-release maintenance is necessary to remediate these bugs when they are found.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Most software is a combination of pre-existing commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) and open-source software components with custom-written code.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] COTS and open-source software is typically updated over time, which can reduce the maintenance burden, but the modifications to these software components will need to be adjusted for in the final product.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Unlike software development, which is focused on meeting specified requirements, software maintenance is driven by events—such as user requests or detection of a bug.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Its main purpose is to preserve the usefulness of the software, usually in the face of changing requirements.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] If conceived of as part of the software development life cycle, maintenance is the last and typically the longest phase of the cycle, comprising 80 to 90 percent of the lifecycle cost.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Other models consider maintenance separate from software development, instead as part of the software maintenance life cycle (SMLC).
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] SMLC models typically include understanding the code, modifying it, and revalidating it.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Frequently, software is delivered in an incomplete state.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Developers will test a product until running out of time or funding, because they face fewer consequences for an imperfect product than going over time or budget.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The transition from the development to the maintenance team is often inefficient, without lists of known issues or validation tests, which the maintenance team will likely recreate.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] After release, members of the development team are likely to be reassigned or otherwise become unavailable.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The maintenance team will require additional resources for the first year after release, both for technical support and fixing defects left over from development.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Initially, software may go through a period of enhancements after release.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] New features are added according to user feedback.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] At some point, the company may decide that it is no longer profitable to make functional improvements, and restrict support to bug fixing and emergency updates.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Changes become increasingly difficult and expensive due to lack of expertise or decaying architecture due to software aging.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] After a product is no longer maintained, and does not receive even this limited level of updating, some vendors will seek to extract revenue from the software as long as possible, even though the product is likely to become increasingly avoided.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Eventually, the software will be withdrawn from the market, although it may remain in use.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] During this process, the software becomes a legacy system.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The first step in the change cycle is receiving a change request from a customer and analyzing it to confirm the problem and decide whether to implement the change.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] This may require input from multiple departments; for example, the marketing team can help evaluate whether the change is expected to bring more business.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Software development effort estimation is a difficult problem, including for maintenance change requests, but the request is likely to be declined if it is too expensive or infeasible.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] If it is decided to implement the request, it can be assigned to a scheduled release and implemented.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Although agile methodology does not have a maintenance phase, the change cycle can be enacted as a scrum sprint.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Understanding existing code is an essential step before modifying it.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The rate of understanding depends both on the code base as well as the skill of the programmer.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Following coding conventions such as using clear function and variable names that correspond to their purpose makes understanding easier.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Use of conditional loop statements only if the code could execute more than once, and eliminating code that will never execute can also increase understandability.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Experienced programmers have an easier time understanding what the code does at a high level.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Software visualization is sometimes used to speed up this process.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Modification to the code may take place in any way.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] On the one hand, it is common to haphazardly apply a quick fix without being granted enough time to update the code documentation.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] On the other hard structured iterative enhancement can begin by changing the top-level requirements document and propagating the change down to lower levels of the system.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Modification often includes code refactoring (improving the structure without changing functionality) and restructuring (improving structure and functionality at the same time).
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Unlike commercial software, free and open source software change cycles are largely restricted to coding and testing, with minimal documentation.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Open-source software projects instead rely on mailing lists and a large number of contributors to understand the code base and fix bugs efficiently.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] An additional problem with maintenance is that nearly every change to code will introduce new bugs or unexpected ripple effects, which require another round of fixes.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Testing can consume most of the maintenance resource for safety-critical code, due to the need to revalidate the entire software if any changes are made.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Revalidation may include code review, regression testing with a subset of unit tests, integration tests, and system tests.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The goal of the testing is to verify that previous functionality is retained, and the new functionality has been added.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The key purpose of software maintenance is ensuring that the product continues to meet usability requirements.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] At times, this may mean extending the product's capabilities beyond what was initially envisioned.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] According to some estimates, enhancement (the latter two categories) comprises some 80 percent of software maintenance.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Maintainability is the quality of software enabling it to be easily modified without breaking existing functionality.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] According to the ISO/IEC 14764 specification, activity to ensure software maintainability prior to release counts as part of software maintenance.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Many software development organizations neglect maintainability, even though doing so will increase long-term costs.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Technical debt is incurred when programmers, often out of laziness or urgency to meet a deadline, choose quick and dirty solutions rather than build maintainability into their code.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] A common cause is underestimates in software development effort estimation, leading to insufficient resources allocated to development.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] One important aspect is having a large amount of automated software tests that can detect if existing functionality is compromised by a change.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] A maintainability index can be calculated with certain formulae from lines-of-code measures, McCabe measures and Halstead complexity measures.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The measurement and tracking of maintainability are intended to help reduce or reverse a system's tendency toward "code entropy" or degraded integrity, and to indicate when it becomes cheaper and/or less risky to rewrite the code than it is to change it.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] A challenge with maintainability is that many software engineering courses do not emphasize it, and give out one-and-done assignments that have clear and unchanging specifications.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Software engineering courses do not cover systems as complex as occur in the real world.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Development engineers who know that they will not be responsible for maintaining the software do not have an incentive to build in maintainability.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Maintenance is often considered an unrewarding job for software engineers, who, if assigned to maintenance, were more likely to quit.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] It often pays less than a comparable job in software development.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The task is often assigned to temporary workers or lesser-skilled staff, although maintenance engineers are also typically older than developers, partly because they must be familiar with outdated technologies.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] In 2008, around 900,000 of the 1.3 million software engineers and programmers working in the United States were doing maintenance.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Companies started separate teams for maintenance, which led to outsourcing this work to a different company, and by the turn of the twenty-first century, sometimes offshoring the work to another country—whether as part of the original company or a separate entity.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] The typical sources of outsourcing are developed countries such as the United States, the United Kingdom, Japan, and Australia, while destinations are usually lower-cost countries such as China, India, Russia, and Ireland.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Reasons for offshoring include taking advantage of lower labor costs, enabling around-the-clock support, reducing time pressure on developers, and to move support closer to the market for the product.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Downsides of offshoring include communication barriers in the form of such factors as time zone and organizational disjunction and cultural differences.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Despite many employers considering maintenance lower-skilled work and the phase of software development most suited to offshoring, it requires close communication with the customer and rapid response, both of which are hampered by these communication difficulties.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] In software engineering, the term legacy system does not have a fixed meaning, but often refers to older systems which are large, difficult to modify, and also necessary for current business needs.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Often legacy systems are written in obsolete programming languages, lack documentation, have a deteriorating structure after years of changes, and depend on experts to keep it operational.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] When dealing with these systems, at some point so much technical debt accumulates that maintenance is not practical or economical.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Despite taking up the lion's share of software development resources, maintenance is the least studied phase of software development.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] Much of the literature has focused on how to develop maintainable code from the outset, with less focus on motivating engineers to make maintainability a priority.
[src:swe-practice/software-maintenance] As of 2020, automated solutions for code refactoring to reduce maintenance effort are an active area of research, as is machine-learning enhanced maintainability assessment.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] The *Jargon File*, a compendium of hacker lore, defines "bit rot" as a jocular explanation for the degradation of a software program over time even if "nothing has changed"; the idea behind this is almost as if the bits that make up the program were subject to radioactive decay.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Several factors are responsible for software rot, including changes to the environment in which the software operates, degradation of compatibility between parts of the software itself, and the emergence of bugs in unused or rarely used code.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] When changes occur in the program's environment, particularly changes which the designer of the program did not anticipate, the software may no longer operate as originally intended.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] For example, many early computer game designers used the CPU clock speed as a timer in their games.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] However, newer CPU clocks were faster, so the gameplay speed increased accordingly, making the games less usable over time.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] There are changes in the environment not related to the program's designer, but its users.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Initially, a user could bring the system into working order, and have it working flawlessly for a certain amount of time.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Information architect Jonas Söderström has named this concept *onceability*, and defines it as "the quality in a technical system that prevents a user from restoring the system, once it has failed".
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Infrequently used portions of code, such as document filters or interfaces designed to be used by other programs, may contain bugs that go unnoticed.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] With changes in user requirements and other external factors, this code may be executed later, thereby exposing the bugs and making the software appear less functional.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Normal maintenance of software and systems may also cause software rot.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] In particular, when a program contains multiple parts which function at arm's length from one another, failing to consider how changes to one part that affect the others may introduce bugs.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] In some cases, this may take the form of libraries that the software uses being changed in a way which adversely affects the software.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] If the old version of a library that previously worked with the software can no longer be used due to conflicts with other software or security flaws that were found in the old version, there may no longer be a viable version of a needed library for the program to use.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Modern commercial software often connects to an online server for license verification and accessing information.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] If the online service powering the software is shut down, it may stop working.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Since the late 2010s most websites use secure HTTPS connections.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] However this requires encryption keys called root certificates which have expiration dates.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] After the certificates expire the device loses connectivity to most websites unless the keys are continuously updated.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Another issue is that in March 2021 old encryption standards TLS 1.0 and TLS 1.1 were deprecated.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] This means that operating systems, browsers and other online software that do not support at least TLS 1.2 cannot connect to most websites, even to download patches or update the browser, if these are available.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] This is occasionally called the "TLS apocalypse".
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Products that cannot connect to most websites include PowerMacs, old Unix boxes and Microsoft Windows versions older than Server 2008/Windows 7 (at least without the use of a third-party browser).
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] The Internet Explorer 8 browser in Server 2008/Windows 7 does support TLS 1.2 but it is disabled by default.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Software rot is usually classified as being either "dormant rot" or "active rot".
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Software that is not currently being used gradually becomes unusable as the remainder of the application changes.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Changes in user requirements and the software environment also contribute to the deterioration.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Software that is being continuously modified may lose its integrity over time if proper mitigating processes are not consistently applied.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] However, much software requires continuous changes to meet new requirements and correct bugs, and re-engineering software each time a change is made is rarely practical.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] This creates what is essentially an evolution process for the program, causing it to depart from the original engineered design.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] As a consequence of this and a changing environment, assumptions made by the original designers may be invalidated, thereby introducing bugs.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] In practice, adding new features may be prioritized over updating documentation; without documentation, however, it is possible for specific knowledge pertaining to parts of the program to be lost.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] To some extent, this can be mitigated by following best current practices for coding conventions.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Active software rot slows once an application is near the end of its commercial life and further development ceases.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Users often learn to work around any remaining software bugs, and the behaviour of the software becomes consistent as nothing is changing.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Many seminal programs from the early days of AI research have suffered from irreparable software rot.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Suppose an administrator creates a forum using open source forum software, and then heavily modifies it by adding new features and options.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] This process requires extensive modifications to existing code and deviation from the original functionality of that software.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Suppose a webmaster installs the latest version of MediaWiki, the software that powers wikis such as Wikipedia, then never applies any updates.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Over time, the web host is likely to update their versions of the programming language (such as PHP) and the database (such as MariaDB) without consulting the webmaster.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] After a long enough time, this will eventually break complex websites that have not been updated, because the latest versions of PHP and MariaDB will have breaking changes as they hard deprecate certain built-in functions, breaking backwards compatibility and causing fatal errors.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Other problems that can arise with un-updated website software include security vulnerabilities and spam.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Refactoring is a means of addressing the problem of software rot.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] It is described as the process of rewriting existing code to improve its structure without affecting its external behaviour.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] This includes removing dead code and rewriting sections that have been modified extensively and no longer work efficiently.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Care must be taken not to change the software's external behaviour, as this could introduce incompatibilities and thereby itself contribute to software rot.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Some design principles to consider when it comes to refactoring is maintaining the hierarchical structure of the code and implementing abstraction to simplify and generalize code structures.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Software entropy describes a tendency for repairs and modifications to a software system to cause it to gradually lose structure or increase in complexity.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Manny Lehman used the term entropy in 1974 to describe the complexity of a software system, and to draw an analogy to the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] Lehman's laws of software evolution state that a complex software system will require continuous modifications to maintain its relevance to the environment around it, and that such modifications will increase the system's entropy unless specific work is done to reduce it.
[src:swe-practice/software-rot] In 1999, Andrew Hunt and David Thomas use fixing broken windows as a metaphor for avoiding software entropy in software development.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.8.1, 1.9.0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.8, 1.81, 1.82.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added or for marketing purposes.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Version numbers are often used to identify copies of a software product and compare them against another copy in a collaborative version control system.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Within software development teams, version control is used to keep track of incrementally-different versions of information in order to be able to roll any changes back.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Modern computer software is often tracked using two different software versioning schemes: an internal version number, which may be incremented many times in a single day, and a release version, which typically changes far less often.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Historically, file numbers were especially used in public administration and corporations to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This practice was introduced to computer files for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX file system for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a standardized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy, which is particularly useful when using software libraries, frameworks, and command-line applications.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] File numbers were used especially in public administration, as well as companies, to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] For computer files this practice was introduced for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX filesystem for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Later lists of files including their versions were added, and dependencies amongst them.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Linux distributions like Debian, with its dpkg, early on created package management software which could resolve dependencies between their packages.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Debian's first try was that a package knew other packages which depended on it.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] From 1994 on this idea was inverted, so a package that knew the packages it needed.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] When installing a package, dependency resolution was used to automatically calculate the packages needed as well, and install them with the desired package.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] To facilitate upgrades, minimum package versions were introduced.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Thus the numbering scheme needed to tell which version was newer than the required one.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In sequence-based software versioning schemes, each software release is assigned a unique identifier that consists of one or more sequences of numbers or letters.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This is the extent of the commonality; schemes vary widely in areas such as the number of sequences, the attribution of meaning to individual sequences, and the means of incrementing the sequences.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In some schemes, sequence-based identifiers are used to convey the significance of changes between releases.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Semantic versioning (aka SemVer) is a widely adopted version scheme that encodes a version by a three-part version number (Major.Minor.Patch), an optional prerelease tag, and an optional build meta tag.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In this scheme, risk and functionality are the measures of significance.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Breaking changes are indicated by increasing the major number (high risk); new, non-breaking features increment the minor number (medium risk); and all other non-breaking changes increment the patch number (lowest risk).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The presence of a prerelease tag (-alpha, -beta) indicates substantial risk, as does a major number of zero (0.y.z), which is used to indicate a work-in-progress that may contain any level of potentially breaking changes (highest risk).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] As an example of inferring compatibility from a SemVer version, software which relies on version 2.1.5 of an API is compatible with version 2.2.3, but not necessarily with 3.2.4.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] A fourth number may also be used to denote the software build, as was the case for Adobe Flash.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Some companies also include the build date and letters and other characters, such as Lotus 1-2-3 Release 1a.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added, but are not enough to warrant incrementing a major version number; for example, Internet Explorer 5 from 5.1 to 5.5 or Adobe Photoshop 5 to 5.5.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] A different approach is to use the *major* and *minor* numbers along with an alphanumeric string denoting the release type, e.g.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] A software release train using this approach might look like 0.5, 0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9 → 1.0b1, 1.0b2 (with some fixes), 1.0b3 (with more fixes) → 1.0rc1 (if it is stable *enough*), 1.0rc2 (if more bugs are found) → 1.0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] It is a common practice in this scheme to lock out new features and breaking changes during the release candidate phases and, for some teams, even betas are locked down to bug fixes only, to ensure convergence on the target release.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Again, in these examples, the definition of what constitutes a "major" as opposed to a "minor" change is entirely subjective and up to the author, as is what defines a "build", or how a "revision" differs from a "minor" change.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] : The most recent interface number that the library implements.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] : The implementation number of the current interface.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] : The difference between the newest and oldest interfaces that the library implements.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] : others may use a different meaning or simply ignore it.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] A similar problem of relative change significance and versioning nomenclature exists in book publishing, where edition numbers or names can be chosen based on varying criteria.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In most proprietary software, the first released version of a software product has version 1.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Some projects use the major version number to indicate incompatible releases.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Two examples are Apache Portable Runtime (APR) and the FarCry CMS.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Often programmers write new software to be backward compatible.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] For example, IBM z/OS is designed to work properly with 3 consecutive major versions of the operating system running in the same sysplex.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This enables people who run a high availability computer cluster to keep most of the computers up and running while one machine at a time is shut down, upgraded, and restored to service.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Often packet headers and file format include a version number – sometimes the same as the version number of the software that wrote it; other times a "protocol version number" independent of the software version number.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The code to handle old deprecated protocols and file formats is often seen as cruft.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Software in the experimental stage (alpha or beta) often uses a zero in the first ("major") position of the sequence to designate its status.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] However, this scheme is only useful for the early stages, not for upcoming releases with established software where the version number has already progressed past 0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The two purely numeric forms remove the special logic required to handle the comparison of "alpha < beta < rc < no prefix" as found in semantic versioning, at the cost of clarity.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.7.0, 1.8.0, 1.8.1, 1.9.0, 1.10.0, 1.11.0, 1.11.1, 1.11.2, and so on.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.7, 1.8, 1.81, 1.82, 1.9, etc.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Decimal versions were common in the 1980s, for example with NetWare, DOS, and Microsoft Windows, but even in the 2000s have been for example used by Opera and Movable Type.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In the decimal scheme, 1.81 is the minor version following 1.8, while maintenance releases (i.e. bug fixes only) may be denoted with an alphabetic suffix, such as 1.81a or 1.81b.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The standard GNU version numbering scheme is major.minor.revision, but Emacs is a notable example using another scheme where the major number (1) was dropped and a *user site* revision was added which is always zero in original Emacs packages but increased by distributors.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Similarly, Debian package numbers are prefixed with an optional "epoch", which is used to allow the versioning scheme to be changed.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In some cases, developers may decide to reset the major version number.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This is sometimes used to denote a new development phase being released.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] For example, *Minecraft* Alpha ran from version 1.0.0 to 1.2.6, and when Beta was released, it reset the major version number and ran from 1.0 to 1.8.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Once the game was fully released, the major version number again reset to 1.0.0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Some projects use negative version numbers.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] One example is the SmartEiffel compiler which started from −1.0 and counted upwards to 0.0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] To ease sorting, some software packages represent each component of the *major.minor.release* scheme with a fixed width.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Perl represents its version numbers as a floating-point number; for example, Perl's 5.8.7 release can also be represented as 5.008007.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This allows a theoretical version of 5.8.10 to be represented as 5.008010.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Other software packages pack each segment into a fixed bit width; for example, on Microsoft Windows, version number 6.3.9600.16384 would be represented as hexadecimal 0x0006000325804000.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The floating-point scheme breaks down if any segment of the version number exceeds 999; a packed-binary scheme employing 16 bits apiece breaks down after 65535.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Between the 1.0 and the 2.6.x series, the Linux kernel used odd minor version numbers to denote development releases and even minor version numbers to denote stable releases.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] For example, Linux 2.3 was a development family of the second major design of the Linux kernel, and Linux 2.4 was the stable release family that Linux 2.3 matured into.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] After the minor version number in the Linux kernel is the release number, in ascending order; for example, Linux 2.4.0 → Linux 2.4.22.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Since the 2004 release of the 2.6 kernel, Linux no longer uses this system, and has a much shorter release cycle.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The same odd-even system is used by some other software with long release cycles, such as Node.js up to version 0.12 as well as WineHQ.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Many projects use a date-based versioning scheme called **Calendar Versioning** (aka **CalVer**).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Ubuntu is one example of a project using calendar versioning; Ubuntu 18.04, for example, was released in April 2018.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This has the advantage of being easily relatable to development schedules and support timelines.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Some video games also use date as versioning, for example the arcade game *Street Fighter EX*.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] At startup it displays the version number as a date plus a region code, for example *961219 ASIA*.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] When using dates in versioning, for instance, file names, it is common to use the ISO 8601 scheme *YYYY-MM-DD*, as this is easily string-sorted in increasing or decreasing order.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The Wine project formerly used a date versioning scheme, which used the year followed by the month followed by the day of the release; for example, "Wine 20040505".
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The earliest development builds of *Minecraft* had a similar version formatting, but instead used DDHHMM, for example rd-131655 was created on the 13th (of May 2009) at 16:21.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Microsoft Office build numbers are an encoded date: the first two digits indicate the number of months that have passed from the January of the year in which the project started (with each major Office release being a different project), while the last two digits indicate the day of that month.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] So 3419 is the 19th day of the 34th month after the month of January of the year the project started.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Other examples that identify versions by year include Adobe Illustrator 88 and WordPerfect Office 2003.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] When a year is used to denote version, it is generally for marketing purposes, and an actual version number also exists.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] For example, Windows 95 is internally versioned as MS-DOS 7.00 and Windows 4.00; likewise, Windows 2000 is internally versioned as NT 5.0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Some software producers use different schemes to denote releases of their software.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The Debian project uses a major/minor versioning scheme for releases of its operating system but uses code names from the movie *Toy Story* during development to refer to stable, unstable, and testing releases.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] BLAG Linux and GNU features very large version numbers: major releases have numbers such as 50000 and 60000, while minor releases increase the number by 1 (e.g.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Alpha and beta releases are given decimal version numbers slightly less than the major release number, such as 19999.00071 for alpha 1 of version 20000, and 29999.50000 for beta 2 of version 30000.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Urbit uses *Kelvin versioning* (named after the absolute Kelvin temperature scale): software versions start at a high number and count down to version 0, at which point the software is considered finished and no further modifications are made.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In conjunction with the various versioning schemes listed above, a system for denoting prerelease versions is generally used, as the program makes its way through the stages of the software release life cycle.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Programs that are in an early stage are often called "alpha" software, after the first letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] After they mature but are not yet ready for release, they may be called "beta" software, after the second letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Generally alpha software is tested by developers only, while beta software is distributed for community testing.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Some systems use numerical versions less than 1 (such as 0.9), to suggest their approach toward a final "1.0" release.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This is a common convention in open source software.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] However, if the prerelease version is for an existing software package (e.g. version 2.5), then an "a" or "alpha" may be appended to the version number.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] So the alpha version of the 2.5 release might be identified as 2.5a or 2.5.a.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Version numbers are used in practical terms by the consumer, or client, to identify or compare their copy of the software product against another copy, such as the newest version released by the developer.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] For the programmer or company, versioning is often used on a revision-by-revision basis, where individual parts of the software are compared and contrasted with newer or older revisions of those same parts, often in a collaborative version control system.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a formalized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The purpose of such policies is to make it easier for other programmers to know when code changes are likely to break things they have written.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Such policies are especially important for software libraries and frameworks, but may also be very useful for command-line applications (which may be called from other applications) and for other applications (which may be scripted and/or extended by third parties).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] A **software release train** is a form of software release schedule in which a number of distinct series of versioned software releases for multiple products are released as a number of different "trains" on a regular schedule.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Generally, for each product line, a number of different release trains are running at a given time, with each train moving from initial release to eventual maturity and retirement on a planned schedule.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Users may experiment with a newer release train before adopting it for production, allowing them to experiment with newer, "raw", releases early, while continuing to follow the previous train's point releases for their production systems prior to moving to the new release train as it becomes mature.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Cisco's IOS software platform used a release train schedule with many distinct trains for many years.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] More recently, a number of other platforms including Firefox and Fenix for Android, Eclipse, LibreOffice, Ubuntu, Fedora, Python, digiKam and VMware have adopted the release train model.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Software may have an "internal" version number which differs from the version number shown in the product name (and which typically follows version numbering rules more consistently).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Windows 10 was initially intended to be NT 6.4, as the earliest Technical Preview build shared to the public is numbered 6.4.9841.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] However, that did not last as the version of Windows 10 was quickly artificially increased to 10.0 to align with the commercial name, resulting in the first released version of the operating system being numbered 10.0.10240.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Note, however, that Windows NT is only on its fifth major revision, as its first release was numbered 3.1 (to match the then-current Windows release number) and the Windows 10 launching made a version leap from 6.3 to 10.0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] A relatively common practice is to make major jumps in version numbers for marketing reasons.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Sometimes software vendors just bypass the 1.0 release or quickly release a release with a subsequent version number because 1.0 software is considered by many customers too immature to trust with production deployments.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] For example, as in the case of dBase II, a product is launched with a version number that implies that it is more mature than it is.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Other times version numbers are increased to match those of competitors.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This can be seen in many examples of product version numbering by Microsoft, America Online, Sun Solaris, Java Virtual Machine, SCO Unix, WordPerfect.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Microsoft Access jumped from version 2.0 to version 7.0, to match the version number of Microsoft Word.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Another example of keeping up with competitors is when Slackware Linux jumped from version 4 to version 7 in 1999.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This approach, panned by many because it breaks the semantic significance of the sections of the version number, has been adopted by an increasing number of vendors including Mozilla (for Firefox) and Google (for Google Chrome).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Sun also dropped the first digit for Solaris, where Solaris 2.8 (or 2.9) is referred to as Solaris 8 (or 9) in marketing materials.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] A similar jump took place with the Asterisk open-source PBX construction kit in the early 2010s, whose project leads announced that the current version 1.8.x would soon be followed by version 10.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The free-software and open source communities tend to release software early and often.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Initial versions are numbers less than 1, with these 0.x version used to convey that the software is incomplete and not reliable enough for general release or usable in its current state.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Backward-incompatible changes are common with 0.x versions.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Version 1.0 is used as a major milestone, indicating that the software has at least all major features plus functions the developers wanted to get into that version, and is considered reliable enough for general release.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] A good example of this is the Linux kernel, which was first released as version 0.01 in 1991, and took until 1994 to reach version 1.0.0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The developers of the arcade game emulator MAME do not ever intend to release a version 1.0 of the program because there will always be more arcade games to emulate and thus the project can never be truly completed.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Accordingly, version 0.99 was followed by version 0.100.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The Python Software Foundation has published PEP 440 – Version Identification and Dependency Specification, outlining their own flexible scheme, that defines an epoch segment, a release segment, prerelease and post-release segments and a development release segment.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] TeX has an idiosyncratic version numbering system, an unusual feature invented by its developer Donald Knuth.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Since version 3.1, updates have been indicated by adding an extra digit at the end, so that the version number asymptotically approaches the number π, so 3.14 effectively means 3.2 in semantic versioning.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] (This is a form of unary numbering; the version number is the number of digits.) Since 2021, the version number has been 3.141592653.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This is a reflection of TeX being very stable, and only minor updates are anticipated.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] TeX developer Donald Knuth has stated that the *"absolutely final change (to be made after [his] death)"* will be to change the version number to π, at which point all remaining bugs will become permanent features.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In a similar way, the version number of Metafont asymptotically approaches Euler's number, e.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Metafont was also devised by Donald Knuth as a companion to his TeX typesetting system.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] During the era of the classic Mac OS, minor version numbers rarely went beyond ".1".
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] When they did, they usually jumped straight to ".5", suggesting the release was "more significant".
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Thus, "8.5" was marketed as its own release, representing "Mac OS 8 and a half", and 8.6 effectively meant "8.5.1".
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Mac OS X departed from this trend, in large part because "X" (the Roman numeral for 10) was in the name of the product.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] As a result, all versions of OS X began with the number 10.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The first major release of OS X was given the version number 10.0, but the next major release was not 11.0.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Instead, it was numbered 10.1, followed by 10.2, 10.3, and so on for each subsequent major release.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Thus the 11th major version of OS X was labeled "10.10".
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Even though the "X" was dropped from the name as of macOS 10.12, this numbering scheme continued through macOS 10.15.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Under the "X"-based versioning scheme, the third number (instead of the second) denoted a minor release, and additional updates below this level, as well as updates to a given major version of OS X coming after the release of a new major version, were titled Supplemental Updates.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The Roman numeral X was concurrently leveraged for marketing purposes across multiple product lines.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Both QuickTime and Final Cut Pro jumped from version 7 directly to version 10, QuickTime X and Final Cut Pro X.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Like Mac OS X itself, the products were not upgrades to previous versions, but brand-new programs.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] As with OS X, major releases for these programs incremented the second digit and minor releases were denoted using a third digit.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The "X" was dropped from Final Cut's name with the release of macOS 11.0 (see below), and QuickTime's branding became moot when the framework was deprecated in favor of AVFoundation in 2011 (the program for playing QuickTime video was only named QuickTime Player from the start).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Apple's next macOS release, provisionally numbered 10.16, was officially announced as macOS 11 at WWDC in June 2020, and released in November 2020.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The following macOS version, macOS Monterey, was released in October 2021 and bumped its major version number to 12.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In June 2025, Apple announced an unified versioning scheme, using the year next to the release date, similar to model years in vehicles.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The versions that were released in the fall of 2025 are iOS 26, macOS 26, iPadOS 26, tvOS 26, watchOS 26 and visionOS 26.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The Microsoft Windows operating system was first labelled with standard version numbers for Windows 1.01 through Windows 3.2.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] After this Microsoft excluded the version number from the product name.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] For Windows 95 (version 4.0), Windows 98 (4.10) and Windows 2000 (5.0), year of the release was included in the product title.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] After Windows 2000, Microsoft created the Windows Server family which continued the year-based style with a difference: For minor releases, Microsoft suffixed "R2" to the title, e.g., Windows Server 2008 R2 (version 6.1).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] This style had remained consistent to this date.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The client versions of Windows however did not adopt a consistent style.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] First, they received names with arbitrary alphanumeric suffixes as with Windows Me (4.90), Windows XP (5.1), and Windows Vista (6.0).
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Then, once again Microsoft adopted incremental numbers in the title, but this time, they were not versioning numbers; the version numbers of Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows 8.1 are respectively 6.1, 6.2 and 6.3.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] In Windows 10, the version number leaped to 10.0 and subsequent updates to the OS only incremented build number (which is date-based) and update build revision (UBR) number.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] The successor of Windows 10, Windows 11, was released on October 5, 2021.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Despite being named "11", the new Windows release did not bump its major version number to 11.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Instead, it stayed at the same version number of 10.0, used by Windows 10.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Some computer file systems, such as the OpenVMS Filesystem, also keep versions for files.
[src:swe-practice/software-versioning] Technical drawing and CAD software files may also use some kind of primitive versioning number to keep track of changes.
[src:swe-practice/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The **Twelve-Factor App methodology** is a methodology for building software-as-a-service applications.
[src:swe-practice/twelve-factor-app-methodology] These best practices are designed to enable applications to be built with portability and resilience when deployed to the web.
[src:swe-practice/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The methodology was drafted by developers at Heroku, a platform-as-a-service company, and was first presented by Adam Wiggins circa 2011.
[src:swe-practice/twelve-factor-app-methodology] An Nginx architect argued that the relevance of the Twelve-Factor app concept is somewhat specific to Heroku, while introducing their own (Nginx's) proposed architecture for microservices.
[src:swe-practice/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The twelve factors are however cited as a baseline from which to adapt or extend.
